text: this fact pattern doesn't indicate some conspiracy or concerning circumstances or behavior. just a very bad, sad series of events and actions.

the ship's owners+operators were contacted, didn't respond. creditors showed up and made claims. ultimately, the ship and its contents were seized by lebanese govt and stored (unsafely) to try to figure out what to do with this large, dangerous, relatively valueless store.

according to some published legal docs, 6yrs ago a ship from moldova stopped in beirut with technical difficulty. was found to be unsafely transporting 2,750 tons of ammonium nitrate to mozambique (likely for sale to farmers)...

beirut followup.. ammonium nitrate is one of the world's most common fertilizers. typical US corn farmers use 200-500lbs per acre. 2,750 tons (beirut store) is a small amt - would fertilize ~10-30k acres corn (90m corn acres in US). market value of 2,750tons is ~$1.5m

text: what is clear, is we shouldn't be chasing People, Places, and Processes that AREN'T dramatically affecting risk (i.e. going to the beach on warm sunny day) yet we include as part of our naive binary "lockdown" narrative and penalize/shame.
context_annotations: [{'domain': {'id': '123', 'name': 'Ongoing News Story', 'description': "Ongoing News Stories like 'Brexit'"}, 'entity': {'id': '1220701888179359745', 'name': 'COVID-19'}}]

text: these can be broken down for People, Places, and Processes. the triggers for which People, Places, Processes change and when are less clear. work to be done, but we have enough to get started with a first phase for each.

it's clear there are a few things we can do that may affect a minority of our normal active behavior that could eliminate MOST of the risk/ICU beds/deaths and give us all the time we need to catch up with antibody therapies.

onsite infection testing seems unrealistic. there exists no on-demand active infection testing today. Abbott system is slow/expensive. CRISPR systems could work but not scaled/approved. but temp checks could be a good proxy for catching ~40% of active infections and cheap/instant

lots of time and attention being spent on Processes that don't make sense. antibody passports don't make sense until 40%+ infected rates (otherwise, you aren't changing anything anyway w low pop count).

Processes can be dependent or independent of People or Places. face masks in all indoor spaces seems like it could eliminate majority of transmissions (china, korea, japan, singapore behavior as predictor). could hand sanitizing + no handshakes/kissing non-family cover the rest?

indoor Places with an average radial density of <3 feet seem especially risky, incl bars, clubs, concerts, casinos, buses, trains, planes. could keeping just these Places closed or managing Processes in these risky Places cut majority of transmissions?

for Places, it seems unlikely that the virus is high risk in outside air (it's still a water-droplet dependent virus, moisture, viral proteins, & RNA degrade rapidly with sunlight, wind, and a lack of steel surfaces). restricting outdoor access is non-sensical.

for People, age > 65 OR People with diabetes, high BMI, high blood pressure, or are immunocompromised, the risk of death may be as much as 85x the rest of the population. thus, restricting this minority's exposure seems like it could manage down the majority of ICU beds/death.

luckily, for each of PPP, there appear to be massively asymmetric risk profiles. this is good news, because by restricting a minority of things, we can reduce a majority of the risk and keep ICU beds and deaths to low levels.

defining rules and triggers for PPP makes the most sense and we should be talking about policy w/in this framework to make progress back to normalcy. we are already seeing governments (i.e. Israel) approach change this way.

thus, it's not ideal to talk abt binary states. and it's non-sensical to believe we can "crush" the virus. even if # infected ppl in US fell to 50 we'd be where we were early March & infected would expand as before w/o a change in PPP. you can't just "return to normal"

we aren't in a binary lockdown today. in sf, for example, anyone can go to the grocery store or "exercise outside". there are some processes in place (i.e. must wear masks to enter the grocery store; but not req'd to do temp checking on entry). our "lockdown" is already nuanced.

- new data indicates asymptomatic transmission increases need for gen pop wearing masks
- virus itself not airborne, virus transmitted in droplet particles in the air and on surfaces
- treatment not needed with mild symptoms
- high-risk patients should consider HCL w tracking

- if you have antibodies, it's not FULLY ANSWERED that you are immune, but some papers show that you can't be re-infected, w some anecdotal data of reinfection (unproven)

- 8 different vaccine approaches with 47 candidate compounds ... expect a vaccine at least 12 months from now

- COVID-19 vaccine already being trialed

text:
- may need high dose 800mg/day of HCL
- hard to make any clear statement at this point on HCL -- good safety signals but no real data to draw conclusions at this point
- french study was people EXPECTED to do well so hard to say if HCL+zpak was useful

- HCL trial on mild patients from china saw 13/15 on HCL get to no viral load on day 7, 14/15 on NO HCL got to no viral load on day 7.. negligible effect on safety or clinical outcome
- 62 patient study showed 1-day reduction in fever/cough but generally this was not clear study

- hydroxychloroquine is an antiviral and antiinflammatory
- most patients gets better and most patients see decline in viral load without treatment... the HCL series from France did not account for NO HCL as a treatment course

treatment:
- can't draw any conclusions from published data on remdesivir at this point; 5 clinical trials underway -expecting readouts any day 
- compassionate use program closed as expanded access program underway now for intubated patients w/o multi-organ failure

- not seeing a lot of co-infection generally; studies range 5-14%, one study (not peer reviewed came in at 22%)
- ICU mortality study comparison data interesting: china ~70%, US 48% -- better care, treatment, or ICU admission bias? is survival improving with learnings about care?
- 25-30% mortality in cancer patients infected and admitted, however 58% of those patients had lung cancer and 42% on active chemo (immune suppression); so not all cancer patients equally at risk

- c19 causes systemic inflammation, not just in lungs, seeing gut and ocular manifestations too
- ocular issues manifesting as conjunctivitis, WITHOUT co-infection typically, seen in about 32% of patients

clinical:
- taste and smell disorders in 34% of patients in a small study, mostly younger women and study was done later in disease course
- not clear how widespread smell/taste issues are at this point, mechanism not clearly understood
- anecdotally, smell/taste recovery likely

- viral load highest during early stage of disease
- sputum from lungs has highest viral content but hard to produce/isolate, thus double oral/nasal swab
- best case still 16% false negative w PCR

testing:
- considers abbott and cepheid systems helpful in creating point-of-care <1 hr PCR detection (still hard to scale or address volume issues but helps in small hospital setting)
- sensitivity of PCR tests now measured based on swab type: oral 56%, nasal 76%, oral+nasal 84%

- jingle from Riverside county "Stay in place, maintain space, cover your face" 
- each action reduces transmission rates and R drops
- success in singapore,hongkong from combo isolation, testing, tracing, strategic antibody detection

- IHME model currently predicting ~80k net deaths in US with peak daily death rate in mid-April
- genetic analysis of virus in Bay Area patients indicates 3-4 unique strains.. Bay Area NOT just community spread but seems to have acquired virus from multiple land/sea/air vectors

- net mortality rate 10-20x seasonal flu, likely closer to 10x due to lack of testing and undercounting cases
- definitely NOT seeing deaths in younger age groups
- US seeing more deaths in middle age groups likely due to sig higher prevalence of pre-existing conditions in US pop

- outbreak now much worse in Europe and US than it ever was in China 
- key metric to watch is daily new cases per 1M pop 
- china peaked at 10, spain steady over past week at 173, italy steady over past week at 100, US now at 90 rising every day (these are my calcs)

epidemiology:
- asian response to pandemic was informed by their experience with SARS. already common practice to wear masks in public, knew how to rapidly test & trace, isolation protocol planned & ready; thus, better curve flattening over US

text: fortunately, it seems these kits are getting FDA approved and coming to market en masse now, i hope this enables other more organized teams to run these analyses in their communities and get mild/asymptomatic population rates estimated quickly and reliably. we will keep going

next steps: 
- i dont want to distribute more test kits until we see test kit performance analysis data
- we will keep ordering/sourcing to scale up program when ready
- we are also working on a protocol to track test reporting

- a local research team is going to run 500 tests from each antibody test manufacturer with actual c19+ patient sera to quantify specificity, sensitivity, and cross-reactivity. they expect to pre-publish in ~2 weeks
- we are donating 500 of our wandfo kits to them for this effort

sensitivity of tests:
- we have found 6 c19 PCR+ patients for verifying wandfo and raybiotech test kits
- 5 positive with raybiotech (mix of IgG/IgM) 
- 2 positive with wandfo
- cross-testing indicates better sensitivity with raybiotech
(cont)

distribution and bias: 
- we give 20 tests to "sourcer" who finds friends/neighbors to volunteer + self-report
- volunteers may be biased to those thinking they have/had c19 
- sourcers sending tests out of area & to known c19+ patients (violate protocol)
- <60% tests report back

anecdotes emerged that indicate there is a very real mild/asymptomatic pop out there..frequent traveler, thought he had bad cold last mo; spring breaker back from cabo, feels ok; young worker, tired. i dont think we can draw any conclusions given bias and size of data set

we traced positives we report here to verify. i think tests underrepresent true positives based on performance w c19 PCR+ patient sera. however 0.5% of SF population (our limited data shows) is 10x reported rate. but i dont have faith in our data given bias, cleanliness, & scale.

data:
- 437 reported results
- 11 positive, 401 neg, 24 inconclusive (user error)
- of positive:
-- 4 out of state (ppl shipped test to sick friends)
-- 3 known cases (broke protocol)
-- 2/392 in SF, 2/40 on peninsula
-- 100% of positives reported SOME symptoms vs 71% of negs

antibody testing update:
- now seeing some asymptomatic infections in general pop
- don't have enough high quality day to conclude anything
- <60% of tests distributed are reporting
- there is clear bias in the data
- there are sensitivity issues with test kits
(details follow)

there is a new technology based on CRISPR that is actively being developed.. a CRISPR molecule with a "guide RNA" matches up to specific SARS-CoV-2 RNA & changes color if match is found. this can be "printed" on strip of paper and turned into an at-home/doc office test..

best solution to test for active infection may NOT be PCR. PCR is best CURRENT solution - costs $6, but requires central lab, 6 step procedure, 45 minutes, and requires people, swabs, and reagents. can we get cheap/fast at-home active infection test? yes, we should, soon...

how do we test everyone? we need to test active infection (RNA) AND past infection (antibodies) cheap/quick to really trace/track. antibody tests now getting approved & coming to market (yay!).. these are cheap (<$10) easy-to-use (finger prick at-home) & fast (10mins)...

for factory/worksite/point-of-care applications, the limitation of 10 tests/hr and $40+/test seems like a big hurdle to overcome - you can't test 2,500 ppl working in a single facility with those metrics. seems more of an edge-case solution than a natl everyone tested solution.

you would need to pool all devices centrally + run 24 hours + would still need to solve last-mile problem (more HCWs, PPE, & swabs) to meaningfully move the needle on natl capacity, and cost would likely be 10x a scaled high-throughput multiplexed PCR testing approach

abbott rapid test announcement yday doesn't seem useful. there are only a few thousand devices out there (+ hard to get), distributed in low-density locations (not where needed), can only run 10 tests/hr, still requires swab w PPE, pricing likely 7x PCR test ($40+)

was told NO ACTIVITY by US govt (federal or local) to buy these tests but lots of private sector interest and tons of folks trying to import and use in US. 1m+ expected to start hitting the US this week .. not FDA approved for diagnostics, questionable use for research. why?

claim that these tests are WHO authorized and being used in korea, australia and italy and that germany just placed an order for 9m tests but i have not been able to independently verify these statements.. if true seems like germany may be testing large % of population

test requires a few drops of blood on a stick from a finger prick. IgM antibodies show up 3-10 days after an active infection and last several months, IgG antibodies show up weeks after an active infection and last years

a big benefit of these tests is time and cost - they take 10 minutes and cost pennies to dollars. as such they can be deployed widely and used for figuring out the true infected population count and tracing/tracking infections over time and space

IgM and IgG antibody tests are not a replacement for RT-PCR tests in diagnosing an active SARS-COV-2 infection. the IgG/IgM tests can be used to identify a past infection - useful for finding asymptomatic ppl; typically ~10% false negative and <1% false positive

text: this analysis doesn't even account for the quality of life effects... how many people living on unemployment will find their way to opioids? how many will see the effects of depression? homelessness?

if we are increasing our national unemployment rate by 5% for each week we are shutdown, it could be argued we are increasing next-year mortality in the working population by 110k people.. a 5-week shutdown would result in half a million incremental deaths in a year

6% increase of 227 is 14; thus, assuming a 160m working population in US, a 1% increase in unemployment would increase next-year mortality by 22,400 people; each 5% increment in unemployment is 110k incremental deaths

what does unemployment do to mortality rates? this is hotly debated but a study (below) shows each 1% increment in unemployment increases next-year mortality by 6%. median age in US is 38. one-year mortality for a 38 yr old is 227//100k..

based on a distribution of circumstances (cash balance, headcount, rev impact etc by different sectors), we can probably assume 5% reduction in headcount for each week without revenue. yesterday, a major NY restaurant chain laid off 90% of employees (2000 ppl) in a day

median small bus revenue is $390k, with 7% op margins, and $12k cash balance (sources provided at end); losing 100% of revenue means 2 weeks of cash if operating expenses stay up! thus, they need to cut employees asap..

social isolation is saving lives.. we can even estimate how many  - Imperial College says up to 2M, but may be much less (<100k?) if key assumptions are off, even by a little bit; we aren't, however, hearing many numbers about the human cost of the economic damage of the shutdown

48% of Americans work for themselves or small local businesses (<10 employees),  10% work in restaurant industry, 5% in travel industry, 4% in energy industry, 3% in retail sales.. some overlap, but likely 2/3 of American jobs are at risk by our active shutdown

text: such models are often viewed as deterministic (this is what’s going to happen) and only at a point in time (the forecast doesn’t change). the reality is these models are probabilistic (create a range of different outcomes) and are dynamic (change all the time with new data)
the imperial college model should not be treated as a static predictor.. it uses a range of assumptions and doesn’t have other potentially important variables
there are other variables that aren’t modeled like distribution of A1c, which may be a key driver of outcome/severity in covid-19 (https://t.co/BhEfWxhqvs)
